docs.abstract: A world championship in Texas is flush with cash and star players as the Professional Pickleball Association tries to turn amateur interest into long-term fandom.
docs.snippet: A world championship in Texas is flush with cash and star players as the Professional Pickleball Association tries to turn amateur interest into long-term fandom.
docs.lead_paragraph: Anna Leigh Waters, a 17-year-old from Delray Beach, Fla., is the world’s top-ranked pickleball player and is widely considered to be the face of America’s fastest-growing sport. But from where she stands, she is still relatively unknown, even among a majority of the racket sport’s fans.

headline.main: The ‘Super Bowl of Pickleball’ Looks to Grow the Sport
headline.print_headline: An Upstart Sport Draws Big Money and Crowds

docs.abstract: A fantasy football championship featured YouTubers, comedians and athletes, with ESPN’s Stephen A. Smith as its guest of honor.
docs.snippet: A fantasy football championship featured YouTubers, comedians and athletes, with ESPN’s Stephen A. Smith as its guest of honor.
docs.lead_paragraph: It was late Sunday evening at Pullman Yards, a former fertilizer plant and industrial complex that now serves as an entertainment venue on the east side of Atlanta, and the YouTuber Kyle Forgeard’s path to victory in a glammed-up fantasy football championship was narrowing.

headline.main: Glitz, Glamour and Trash-Talk at the ‘Ultimate Fantasy Competition’

docs.abstract: Writing for anglers and amateurs alike, he found that the sport can reveal as much about people as it does about fish.
docs.snippet: Writing for anglers and amateurs alike, he found that the sport can reveal as much about people as it does about fish.
docs.lead_paragraph: John Gierach, a fly fisherman who was as skilled with a rod and reel as he was with words, producing hundreds of articles and more than 20 books, including “Even Brook Trout Get the Blues” and “Sex, Death and Fly-Fishing,” died on Oct. 3 in Longmont, Colo. He was 77.

headline.main: John Gierach, Fly Fishing Author With Wit and Wisdom, Dies at 77
headline.print_headline: John Gierach, 77, Fly Fishing Author Whose Wit and Wisdom Reeled In Readers

docs.abstract: Avid and influential anglers turned out to honor Bob Rich Jr. at the Bonefish & Tarpon Trust’s annual gala in Manhattan.
docs.snippet: Avid and influential anglers turned out to honor Bob Rich Jr. at the Bonefish & Tarpon Trust’s annual gala in Manhattan.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Tuesday night, on a quiet stretch of Park Avenue, some of the most illustrious figures in fly fishing, marine science, conservation and frozen food gathered to celebrate one of the things that brings them all together — the sea.

headline.main: It Is ‘All About the Fish’ on Park Ave.

docs.abstract: For centuries, the sport’s wooden sticks have been made from Ireland’s ash trees. But with a disease destroying forests, the ancient game is turning to different materials.
docs.snippet: For centuries, the sport’s wooden sticks have been made from Ireland’s ash trees. But with a disease destroying forests, the ancient game is turning to different materials.
docs.lead_paragraph: The horde of helmeted players raced up the field like warriors headed into battle, with the slap of a ball against the wooden sticks they wielded, known as hurleys, ringing out as they sped toward the goal posts.

headline.main: Hurling in Ireland: Is the ‘Clash of the Ash’ Becoming a ‘Battle of Bamboo’?
headline.print_headline: As Ash Trees Die, an Ancient Irish Game Adapts

docs.abstract: In each of New York City’s boroughs, decrepit piers that once fed city industries have been brought back to life. Out over the water, they offer beauty, fun and respite from the city’s buzz.
docs.snippet: In each of New York City’s boroughs, decrepit piers that once fed city industries have been brought back to life. Out over the water, they offer beauty, fun and respite from the city’s buzz.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the sun comes out, New Yorkers flock to the city’s piers. They bring picnic blankets and coolers, sunscreen and speakers, to places where decades ago longshoremen unloaded goods from cargo ships.

headline.main: New York City’s Piers, Once Abandoned, Are Now Full of Life
headline.print_headline: On the Waterfront, a Break From Urban Life
